place.name: WARHAM
place.gazetteerText: WARHAM (All Saints and St. Mary), two parishes in Walsingham district, Norfolk; 2 and 2½ miles SSE of Wells r. station. Post town, Wells, Norfolk. Acres, 1,774 and 3,066; of which 600 and 1,010 are water. Real property, £2,995. Pop., 318 and 74. Houses, 69 and 13. The manors belong to the Earl of Leicester. There is a Danish camp of 9 acres. The livings are conjoint rectories in the diocese of Norwich. Value, £600.* Patron, the Earl of Leicester. A. S. church is good; but St. M.'s is extinct. There is a national school. (In 1870-72, John Marius Wilson's Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales)

place.name: WARHAM ST MARY
place.gazetteerText: Warham St Mary, par., Norfolk, adjacent to Warham All Saints, 2056 ac. land and 1010 water, pop. 67. (In 1887, John Bartholomew's Gazetteer of the British Isles)
